## 5. Architecture diagram (with Postgres)

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  subgraph OnPrem
    OP_K8S[Kubernetes Cluster]
    OP_PG[Postgres]
    OP_PROM[Prometheus]
    OP_RMQ[RabbitMQ]
  end

  subgraph AWS
    VPC[VPC]
    subgraph EKSCluster[EKS Cluster]
      APP[Workloads]
    end
    RDS[(RDS Postgres)]
    AMP[Amazon Managed Prometheus]
    AMQ[Amazon MQ (RabbitMQ)]
  end

  OP_K8S -->|Migrate workloads| EKSCluster
  OP_PG -->|Data migration| RDS
  OP_PROM -->|Metrics migration| AMP
  OP_RMQ -->|Queue migration| AMQ

  EKSCluster --> RDS
  EKSCluster --> AMP
  EKSCluster --> AMQ
```

---

## 6. How your organisation uses this

1. **Adopt repo template** for migration projects.
2. Open in **Claude Code**.
3. Run `/design`  
   - Team co‑designs AWS target (EKS, RDS Postgres, Amazon MQ, AMP).
4. Once design is agreed, run `/automate`  
   - Claude generates/refines Terraform modules and envs.
5. Use `terraform/envs/sandbox` locally or via CI to deploy to sandbox.
6. Run `/checklist` before:
   - First sandbox deploy  
   - First staging deploy  
   - First prod deploy  
7. Wire `.github/workflows` to AWS accounts (OIDC or org‑approved method).
8. Iterate design/automation/checklist for each migration wave.

If you want, next step we can align this with your **actual AWS org structure** (multi‑account, landing zone, naming/tagging standards) so it drops into your environment with minimal friction.
